{{Infobox magazine | title = Black Enterprise | image_file = Black_Enterprise_May_2008.jpg | image_caption = | image_size = <!-- 220px (the default if no size is stated) --> | image_alt = | editor = Derek T. Dingle | editor_title = [[Editor-in-Chief]] | previous_editor = | staff_writer = | frequency = Bimonthly | total_circulation = 534,752<ref>{{cite web |url=http://abcas3.auditedmedia.com/ecirc/magtitlesearch.asp |title= Alliance for Audited Media Snapshot Report – 6/30/2013 |date= June 30, 2013|publisher= [[Alliance for Audited Media]]|accessdate=February 2, 2014}}</ref> | circulation_year = 2013 | category = | company = Earl G. Graves Publishing Company, Inc. | publisher = [[Earl G. Graves Sr.]]'' | firstdate = 1970 | country = [[United States]] | based = [[New York City]] | language = | website = {{URL|http://blackenterprise.com}} | issn = 0006-4165 }}
'''''Black Enterprise''''' is a black-owned multimedia company. Since the 1970s, its flagship product ''Black Enterprise'' magazine has covered [[African-American businesses|African-American businesse]]<nowiki/>s with a readership of 3.7&nbsp;million. The company was founded in 1970 by [[Earl G. Graves Sr.]] It publishes in both print and on digital, an annual listing of the largest African-American companies in the country, or "B.E. 100's", first compiled and published in 1973.<ref>Alfred Edmond, Jr, [http://www.blackenterprise.com/small-business/black-enterprise-be-100s-ranks-largest-black-owned-businesse/ "Black Enterprise Publishes Rankings Of Nation’s Largest Black-Owned Businesses"], ''Black Enterprise'', June 30, 2014.</ref><ref>Caryn Freeman, [http://thegrio.com/2012/05/25/black-enterprise-celebrates-40-years-of-listing-americas-largest-black-companies/ "Black Enterprise celebrates 40 years of listing America’s largest black companies"], The Grio, May 25, 2012.</ref> In 2002 the magazine launched a supplement targeting teens, ''Teenpreneur''.<ref>{{cite news|author1=Rob Kaiser|title=Teen business magazine debuts with parent publication|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2002-09-25/business/0209250263_1_black-enterprise-new-publication-new-businesses|accessdate=August 3, 2015|work=The Chicago Tribune|date=September 25, 2002}}</ref> ''Black Enterprise'' also has two nationally syndicated television shows, ''Our World with Black Enterprise'' and ''Women of Power''.
== History == The magazine was founded by [[Earl G. Graves Sr.]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cnn.com/2007/US/02/02/bhm.profile.bizpol/index.html|title=Political and business leaders: CEOs to beauty empires |publisher=CNN.com|language=en|date=February 5, 2007|access-date=April 12, 2018}}</ref> In January 2006, Graves named his eldest son, [[Earl G. Graves Jr.]] (known as "Butch"), the company’s chief executive officer.<ref>[https://www.bloomberg.com/research/stocks/private/person.asp?personId=4036392&privcapId=4437793 "Company Overview of Earl G. Graves Ltd"], Bloomberg.</ref> Butch joined the company in 1988 after earning his M.B.A. from [[Harvard University]]; he received his bachelor's degree in economics from [[Yale University]] in 1984. He also sits on the board of directors of AutoZone, serving as lead director and chairman of the compensation committee.
''Black Enterprise'' has been profitable since its 10th issue. The company, headquartered in New York City, has 58 employees and had revenues of $22 million in 2017.{{citation needed|date=April 2018}}
== Award == The magazine won the 1997 FOLIO: Editorial Excellence Award<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/corporate-secretary-announces-new-editor-2011-5|title=Corporate Secretary Announces New Editor|work=Business Insider|date=May 25, 2011|access-date=April 12, 2018}}</ref> in the business/finance consumer magazine category.
