{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2016}} {{Use New Zealand English|date=September 2016}} {{Infobox sportsperson | name = Peter Masfen | honorific_suffix = {{post-nominals|country=NZL|CNZM}} | image = | alt = | caption = | birth_name = Peter Hanbury Masfen | birth_date = {{birth date and age|1941|8|9|df=y}}<ref name="FISA profile">{{cite web |url=http://www.worldrowing.com/athletes/athlete/28425/masfen-peter |title=Peter Masfen |accessdate=7 September 2016 |publisher=[[International Rowing Federation]]}}</ref> | birth_place = [[Auckland]], New Zealand | residence = | education = | alma_mater = | occupation = | years_active = | spouse = | height = {{convert|189|cm|ftin|abbr=on}}<ref name=sports-reference>{{cite web |title=Peter Masfen |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/ma/peter-masfen-1.html |publisher=[[Sports Reference]] |accessdate=7 September 2016}}</ref> | weight = {{convert|88|kg|lb|abbr=on}}<ref name=sports-reference /> | sport = Rowing | club = | medaltemplates = }}
'''Peter Hanbury Masfen''' {{post-nominals|country=NZL|CNZM}} (born 9 August 1941) is a New Zealand businessman, philanthropist, and former representative [[Rowing (sport)|rower]]. Regarded as one of the country's most astute businessmen, he is best known for his former shareholding in [[Montana Wines]].
==Private life== Masfen was born in 1941 in [[Auckland]], New Zealand.<ref>{{cite web |title=Peter Masfen |url=http://www.olympic.org.nz/athletes/peter-masfen/ |publisher=[[New Zealand Olympic Committee]] |accessdate=7 September 2016}}</ref> He received his schooling at [[King's School (Auckland)|King's School]]<ref>{{cite news |title=Old Boys |url=http://kings.school.nz/old-boys/ |accessdate=7 September 2016 |work=[[King's School (Auckland)]]}}</ref> and then [[King's College, Auckland|King's College]] in Auckland.<ref name="Many a reserve">{{cite news |last1=Fletcher |first1=Hamish |title=New Year Honours: Peter Masfen - Many a reserve up his sleeve |url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/business/news/article.cfm?c_id=3&objectid=11567775 |accessdate=7 September 2016 |work=[[The New Zealand Herald]] |date=31 December 2015}}</ref> When he worked for Porter Wigglesworth & Grayburn, he married Joanna Porter, the daughter of principal Rolf Porter. Their sons are Rolf and Anatole and daughter Eugenie.<ref name="Herald corporate profile">{{cite news |last1=Gibson |first1=Anne |title=The corporate grave's comeback kid |url= http://www.nzherald.co.nz/business/news/article.cfm?c_id=3&objectid=10439286 |accessdate=7 September 2016 |work=[[The New Zealand Herald]] |date=12 May 2007}}</ref>
==Involvement in rowing== After having received an invitation to the [[Henley Royal Regatta]], he won the inaugural Prince Phillip Challenge Cup regatta in 1963 in [[Henley-on-Thames]].<ref name="glorious Henley win" /> That year, the Henley regatta was regarded as the event that came closest to a world championship.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Green |first1=David |title=Rowing - International rowing, 1920s to 1980s |url=http://www.teara.govt.nz/en/rowing/page-4 |publisher=[[Te Ara: The Encyclopedia of New Zealand]] |accessdate=7 September 2016 |date=7 September 2013}}</ref> [[Darien Boswell]], [[Dudley Storey]] and [[Alistair Dryden]] made up the other rowers, and [[Robert Page (rower)|Bob Page]] was the [[coxswain (rowing)|cox]].<ref name="glorious Henley win">{{cite news |last1=Leggat |first1=David |title=Rowing: Crew toast 50th anniversary of glorious win |url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/sport/news/article.cfm?c_id=4&objectid=10895045 |accessdate=7 September 2016 |work=[[The New Zealand Herald]] |date=6 July 2013}}</ref>
The same coxed four team then went to the [[1964 Summer Olympics]] in [[Tokyo]], where they placed a disappointing [[Rowing at the 1964 Summer Olympics – Men's coxed four|eighth]].<ref name="glorious Henley win" /><ref>{{cite web |title=New Zealand Rowing at the 1964 Tokyo Summer Games |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/countries/NZL/summer/1964/ROW/ |publisher=[[Sports Reference]] |accessdate=7 September 2016}}</ref> He went to the [[1966 World Rowing Championships]] in Bled, Yugoslavia with the coxed eight,<ref name="Mount Linton" /> where the team came sixth.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Alderson |first1=Andrew |title=Rowing: Time for change after eights disappointment |url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/sport/news/article.cfm?c_id=4&objectid=10808730 |accessdate=7 September 2016 |work=[[The New Zealand Herald]] |date=27 May 2012}}</ref>
Masfen worked as a rowing coach for some time.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Winter |first1=Chloe |title=Rich-lister Peter Masfen honoured for services to business and philanthropy |url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/business/75523849/Rich-lister-Peter-Masfen-honoured-for-services-to-business-and-philanthropy |accessdate=7 September 2016 |work=[[Stuff.co.nz]] |date=31 December 2015}}</ref> He helped fund both the New Zealand women's and men's eight to attend the [[2015 World Rowing Championships]] in [[Aiguebelette-le-Lac]], France, and the [[Rowing at the 2016 Summer Olympics|2016 Summer Olympics]] in [[Rio de Janeiro]], Brazil.<ref name="Many a reserve" />
==Professional life== Masfen started his professional life as an accountant for the accounting firm Porter Wigglesworth & Grayburn, where he eventually became a partner. He consolidated a number of business interest into Collingwood Holdings, which became Corporate Investments Ltd.<ref name="Herald corporate profile" /><ref name="Business Hall of Fame">{{cite web |title=Masfen, Peter Hanbury |url=http://www.businesshalloffame.co.nz/past-laureates/masfen-peter-hanbury/|publisher=New Zealand Business Hall of Fame |accessdate=7 September 2016}}</ref> He invested in the winemaker [[Montana Wines|Montana Group]] and held 21% of its shares until 2001, when the winemaker was taken over by [[Allied Domecq]].<ref name="Herald corporate profile" /> From 2001 to 2005, Masfen was one of the New Zealand representatives on the APEC Business Advisory Council (ABAC).<ref name="New Year Honours" /> In 2003, he took a 50% shareholding in the {{convert|14000|ha}} Mount Linton Station near [[Ohai]] in [[Southland, New Zealand|Southland]].<ref name="Mount Linton">{{cite news |title=Ex-Rower Buys into Ohai Station |url=http://www.mountlinton.co.nz/html/ex-rower_buys_into_ohai_statio.html |accessdate=7 September 2016 |work=[[The Southland Times]] |date=30 July 2003}}</ref>
Masfen is regarded as "one of New Zealand's most shrewd businessmen" and he has often displayed counter-cyclical investment, with a tendency to holding companies longer term.<ref name="Many a reserve" /> The Masfen family is on the rich list published by the ''[[National Business Review]]''. In 2006, the family wealth was estimated at [[New Zealand dollar|NZ$]]330m,<ref name="Herald corporate profile" /> and this had increased to over NZ$400m by 2015.<ref name="Many a reserve" />
==Awards== Masfen was inducted into the New Zealand Business Hall of Fame in 2002.<ref name="Business Hall of Fame" /> He was appointed a [[New Zealand Order of Merit|Companion of the New Zealand Order of Merit]] in the [[2016 New Year Honours (New Zealand)|2016 New Year Honours]], for services to business and philanthropy.<ref name="New Year Honours">{{cite web |title=New Year Honours 2016 - Citations for Companions of the New Zealand Order of Merit |url=https://www.dpmc.govt.nz/honours/lists/ny2016-cnzm |publisher=[[Department of the Prime Minister and Cabinet (New Zealand)|Department of the Prime Minister and Cabinet]] |accessdate=7 September 2016}}</ref>
