{{Infobox}}

The '''World Shipping Council''' ('''WSC''') is the peak [[industry trade group]] representing the international liner shipping industry, which offers regularly scheduled service on fixed schedules. Most liner carriers are  [[containerization|container]] [[shipping line]]s. The WSC is headquartered in [[Washington, D.C.]] and is led by Chief Executive Chief Executive John W. Butler, former general council for the WSC and former President of the Maritime Administrative Bar Association.<ref>http://www.worldshipping.org/</ref>

== Membership==
Council membership includes the world's ten largest container shipping companies<ref>{{cite web|url=https://alphaliner.axsmarine.com/PublicTop100/|title=Alphaliner Top 100|last=|first=|date=June 2018|website=|publisher=Alphaliner|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=}}</ref> as well as smaller firms collectively comprising 90 percent of global container shipments.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldshipping.org/about-the-council/member-corporations|title=Member Companies|last=|first=|date=|year=2018|website=|publisher=World Shipping Council|archiveurl=|archivedate=|dead-url=|accessdate=2018-06-14}}</ref>

In December 2014, it was announced that Christopher Koch, formerly the General Counsel for Sea-Land Service Incorporated and Chief of Staff for U.S.[[Senator John McCain]] and former Senator Slade Gorton would retire as President and CEO in July 2015, with Senior Vice-President and General Counsel, John Butler, assuming the position.<ref>http://www.hellenicshippingnews.com/world-shipping-council-announces-leadership-transition/</ref>

== Activities ==
The Council was formed in 2000<ref name="MANYNJ">{{cite web| title =Remarks before the Maritime Association of the Port of New York and New Jersey | publisher =World Shipping Council |date=October 2000 | url =http://www.worldshipping.org/spe_1.html | accessdate =2008-02-15 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070822123353/http://www.worldshipping.org/spe_1.html <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 2007-08-22}}</ref> to lobby national governments regarding container and cargo shipping regulation, generally in favour of improved [[maritime security]] coupled with deregulation of ports and transport routes.<ref name="MANYNJ" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldshipping.org/about-the-council|title=About the Council|last=|first=|date=|year=2018|website=|publisher=World Shipping Council|archiveurl=|archivedate=|dead-url=|accessdate=2018-06-14}}</ref> The Council also develops draft standards on vessel air emissions and pollution, improvements to seaport [[customs|customs procedures]] and [[International Organization for Standardization|international standards]] for container design and handling.

In 2007, in response to continued problems with containers lost overboard during heavy seas, the WSC and the [[International Chamber of Shipping]] began work on a code of practice for container storage, including crew training on parametric rolling, safer stacking and marking of containers and the securing of above-deck cargo.<ref>{{cite news |title =Banana box slip a worry | work =Lloyd's List Daily Commercial News | publisher =Informa Australia | date =2008-02-07 | url =http://www.lloydslistdcn.com.au/informaoz/LLDCN/home.jsp?source=fresh | accessdate =2008-02-14 }}</ref>

